message: Three years ago, the #ACA began providing healthcare to millions of Americans. Let’s work to strengthen, not dismantle care. #CoverageMatters
#WA01 expects Congress to support their health and economic well-being in the #115thcongress. I will work to do just that. #PeoplesHouse
The #ACA closed the prescription drug donut hole, saving nearly 75,000 #WA seniors an average of $978 in Rx drugs each year. #ACAWorks
I’m honored to serve with these talented women in the 115th Congress. We're working hard to protect our shared values & build an economy that works for everyone.
I joined my colleagues in the traditional reading of our #Constitution to remind us of our oath to support & defend it.

Simply being a woman shouldn’t mean higher medical costs and fewer healthcare options. But make no mistake — if Congress and President-elect Trump succeed in dismantling Obamacare, being a woman will once again be treated as a pre-existing condition. Let’s build on the progress we’ve made, not turn back the clock.  #ProtectOurCare

I was pleased to join colleagues in introducing the West Coast Ocean Protection Act to ban oil drilling along our coasts. Our country should be transitioning to low-carbon energy sources, not taking on the risk of disastrous oil spills. It’s time to make smart investments that will foster a new economy based on clean and renewable energy.

It’s an honor to announce that I’ll join the House Ways and Means Committee, which will be at the forefront of debate on taxes, healthcare and retirement security in the 115th Congress, where Republicans have prioritized tax reform, repealing the Affordable Care Act (ACA), privatizing Medicare and reforming Social Security – all of which will go through the Committee. I believe we need a bipartisan solution that simplifies our tax code for millions of hardworking families and ends tax breaks that haven’t given us a strong return on investment. I’m also committed to ensuring all Americans have access to affordable, quality healthcare and I am prepared to fight against Republican attempts to dismantle Medicare, repeal the ACA and slash Social Security benefits, all of which help millions of families.
ICYMI: Here’s a great op-ed by former Congressman Jim McDermott in the Washington Post on why repealing Obamacare without a replacement is so dangerous. #ProtectOurCare
I joined my colleagues on a bill to create a bipartisan commission to look into foreign interference in the election.

It was an honor to take part in the dedication of the public art piece created by Kevin Pettelle in Monroe, Washington today!
Game time! Let’s go, Seattle Seahawks! #ImIn

Updating our laws to reflect the way the world works in the 21st century has been one of my top priorities in Congress. After spending two decades in the technology sector where things evolve at light speed, it is hard to believe that we’re starting another year with laws that were written for how computing worked in the 1980s. That’s why I’m honored to join colleagues in introducing the bipartisan Email Privacy Act – an overdue step forward for protecting Americans’ civil liberties in the digital age. I hope House and Senate leaders will act swiftly.
Thanks to the Affordable Care Act, the uninsured rate in #WA has fallen by 54%. The #ACAWorks, so let's improve on it, not repeal it.

I have many concerns about Senator Jeff Sessions’ ability to protect and defend the constitutional rights of all Americans regardless of race, religion, gender and sexual orientation. If Sen. Sessions’ record is any indication, he will severely undermine the progress our country has made over the last hundred years. As a member of the House of Representatives, I do not have the opportunity to vote on Senate confirmations. However, I am committed to making sure our government lives up to the core American values of inclusiveness, diversity and tolerance.

Today, I introduced a bill to expand the #ACA tax credit for small businesses, making it more affordable for small employers to offer health coverage to their workers. Rather than repeal, we should focus on commonsense fixes like this:

I'm honored for the opportunity to also serve on the House Budget Committee in the 115th Congress, along with my assignment on Committee on Ways and Means. I look forward to fighting for a forward-looking budget that supports working families and helps create an economy that works for everyone.

Great to join with Congresswoman Susan W. Brooks to kick off today's Women's High Tech Coalition panel on 5G and the #InternetOfThings! As #IoT grows, we need to work together to ensure we have a reliable broadband infrastructure that all of our communities can access.

I’m pleased to join the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative Ambassador Michael Froman in working to ensure we protect good-paying, middle-class jobs in the U.S. #aluminum industry. We cannot allow the unfair practices of China to harm our economic growth – Americans’ livelihoods are at stake, including those in #WA01.

President-elect Donald Trump is breaking his promise to be a President for all Americans by supporting the creation of a Muslim registry. Today, I reintroduced the No Religious Registry Act to prohibit his administration from violating the constitutional rights of Americans. It’s unfortunate I even have to introduce this bill, but intolerance and hate have no place in our government.

A well-maintained #infrastructure is critical to our nation’s economy. I helped introduce legislation that would form an infrastructure bank to make smart investments and fix our crumbling roads and bridges.

Today, House leaders formally began the process of repealing Obamacare — stripping more than 20 million Americans of their health insurance, and taking us back to a time when people went bankrupt because they got sick. What’s worse, there’s still no plan for what comes next. We will not back down from this fight for the millions of hard-working families whose healthcare is now at risk. #ACAworks
Senator Murray, Congresswoman Pramila Jayapal and I held a press conference on the dire consequences for women’s health if the GOP repeals the #ACA and defunds Planned Parenthood.
Blitz the Seahawk, Becca and I are looking forward to another #Seahawks win today! #gohawks #SEAvsATL
The U.S. Forest Service is waiving their fees at day-use recreation sites tomorrow! Find a site and enjoy!
Martin Luther King Jr. continues to be an inspiration as we work to strengthen our communities through civic engagement & equality. #MLKDay
I had a great time volunteering with constituents at the Society of St. Vincent de Paul of Seattle/King County thrift store in Kenmore for #mlkdayofservice.

Yesterday, I joined community faith leaders at Muslim Association of Puget Sound - MAPS to say that we will stand united against hateful actions and rhetoric against our neighbors. The No Religious Registry Act would prohibit any government official from creating a religious registry based on a person's faith.
Congrats to Whatcom Community College on being awarded a National Science Foundation (NSF) grant to provide #STEM scholarships to talented low-income students!

I am gravely concerned that Rep. Tom Price, President-elect Trump’s nominee to lead the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, would turn back the clock for millions of women, #LGBT Americans and hard-working families if confirmed as Secretary. He has long supported dismantling #Medicare and repealing the #AffordableCareAct, which would double premiums and strip 32 million Americans of their health insurance. As Secretary, he could take immediate steps to take away women's access to no-cost birth control, deny access to life-saving care at Planned Parenthood, and allow discrimination against LGBT Americans in healthcare. While I do not have an opportunity to vote on Senate confirmations, I believe our country deserves an HHS Secretary who will defend the health and well-being of all Americans, not just some.

#WomenAreWatching, as are the men who care about them. One day before his inauguration, I joined my colleagues to tell President-elect Trump to reject policies harmful to women's health. Starting tomorrow, his respect for women & families will be judged by his actions, not his words.

Thank you, President Obama, for your commitment to strengthening our communities and moving us forward as one nation. You leave behind a tremendous legacy of accomplishments that have moved our country and world toward fairness, justice and opportunity. Your dedication & compassion to the American people have been an inspiration to many, including myself. So sincerely, #ThanksObama.

Today is the anniversary of the landmark #RoevWade decision, protecting a woman’s constitutional right to make her own healthcare decisions. A woman’s access to care shouldn’t depend on her income or zip code, but 44 years later, we're still fighting to make that a reality. #Roe44
It was great to join #SOTN17 to talk about some issues in #technology where we can make progress with bipartisan support - #computerscience education, #encryption and #IoT to name a few.

The Budget Committee held a brazenly partisan hearing today that the Majority titled “The Failures of Obamacare.” But my office has been flooded with stories from constituents describing how the Affordable Care Act saved their life, or the lives of their loved ones. And while it's easy to get lost in abstract statistics, what’s important to remember is that repealing the #ACA will hurt real people across the country. The American people deserve a Congress willing to work together to improve our healthcare system. Instead, Republicans want to take it all away without a plan for what comes next.

With today’s vote on #HR7, we’re kicking off the new year the same way we spent all of 2016 — attacking women’s health. I took to the House floor to repeat what millions of women proclaimed last weekend: Hear our voices. Respect our bodies. Protect our rights.
Thanks to Rep. Debbie Dingell for making good on our wager with some delicious food from Zingerman's Delicatessen! Detroit Lions Seattle Seahawks

The strength of our local economy depends on a well-maintained, modern infrastructure. I’m pleased U.S. Senate Democrats introduced an #infrastructure plan that includes many smart investments, including $20 billion to help improve access to #broadband for the unserved and underserved populations across America. In the House, I'm fighting to ensure everyone has access to opportunity in the 21st century economy.

I joined my colleagues in urging Speaker Paul Ryan & Senate Majority Leader Senator Mitch McConnell to ensure the Indian Health Care Improvement Act remains intact. Thanks to its permanent reauthorization in the Affordable Care Act, tribal communities have benefited from increased choice and lower out of pocket costs.

Today is International Holocaust Remembrance Day – a day to honor the six million Jews and all who lost their lives at the hands of the Nazis by recommitting to never allow a repeat the darkest days of history. Racism and xenophobia will never have a place in our society, and I will continue to speak out against hateful rhetoric & violent actions. #neveragain
I spoke at the Washington State Department of Commerce's #IoT Summit about the opportunities and challenges #tech innovations are presenting to our communities.

The President's order to ban refugees is in direct conflict with our nation's values of life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness. We have a stringent vetting process already in place that continues to protect our communities. Those seeking refuge from violence and oppression should not be turned away because of their race, ethnicity or religion.

I stood with leaders in #WA today at SeaTac Airport to show it's unacceptable that refugees and visa holders are being turned away because of the President’s misguided executive order. He should stop this cruel targeting of individuals based on religion and nationality. We don’t need to close our doors to keep Americans safe. #NoBan

Today, I wrote to U.S. Customs and Border Protection asking why so little information was communicated during my visit to Seattle-Tacoma International Airport (Sea-Tac) last night. As a Member of Congress with the responsibility to serve my constituents and their families as they interact with taxpayer-funded federal agencies like CBP, it’s concerning that my attempts to get basic information about detainees were rebuffed. #NoBan

Despite all the headlines, the Affordable Care Act (ACA) remains the law of the land, ensuring access to quality, affordable healthcare for millions of Americans. Washingtonians can sign up at www.WAHealthPlanFinder.org until midnight on January 31st. Spread the word.

Tonight, I stand with my colleagues against President Trump’s irresponsible executive order, which has created chaos and fear across the world. This is what happens when the President and his administration issue a reckless order late at night with no thought to the implementation or consideration of the impact on individuals and families. I cosponsored the SOLVE Act to ensure we rescind the President’s executive order, which is nothing more than cruel targeting of individuals based on religion and nationality.
Sally Yates swore an oath to uphold the Constitution and was fired for doing her job. #ThankYouSally for years of faithful public service.

I have serious concerns about the nomination of Neil Gorsuch to the #SCOTUS, particularly given President Trump's repeated promise to only nominate Justices who will overturn #RoevWade. Beyond any commitment he made to the President on a woman's right to choose, Judge Gorsuch already has an alarming record on women's health — having supported the right of corporations to deny workers access to birth control in 2012. I hope the Senate carefully considers the needs of women and families before allowing his nomination to proceed.

President Trump’s new executive order weakens regulations on big banks and puts Americans at risk of another Wall Street #bailout. We need a President who puts our taxpayers first, not #BanksFirst.

The craft brewing and distilling industry is growing and creating jobs and economic opportunities in #WA01. That’s why I cosponsored a bill to modernize the tax code to help support our local brewers, cider makers, vintners and distillers.

I joined my colleagues in introducing legislation that would provide tax relief to working families and make college more affordable. Strong economic growth can only be achieved when all Americans have the opportunity to succeed. These bills will help create a fairer tax code that strengthens our middle class and promotes sustained, long-term growth.

Updating our laws to reflect the way the world works in the 21st century has been one of my top priorities in Congress. When current law affords more protections for a letter in a filing cabinet than an email on a server, it’s clear our policies are woefully outdated. Today’s passage of the #EmailPrivacyAct is a great step forward for Americans’ civil liberties, but it’s now up to the Senate to act and ensure Americans are guaranteed the privacy protections most think they already have.

The American public deserves to know if and how their President’s financial activities will influence his decisions.

President Trump has boasted that his mastery of tax loopholes makes him exceptional to guide us through tax reform. The American public deserves to know if and how their President has been paying his taxes before entrusting him with shepherding far-reaching changes to the current system.
I joined my colleagues in urging the President and the U.S. Department of Agriculture to restore animal welfare data to its website, which helps keep pet owners informed.
A very happy anniversary to the partner who is right there next to me on every step of this path!

On Bloomberg Television today, I reminded President Trump of some #Business101 lessons: 1. You must have a vision and a plan to execute it well; 2. Surround yourself with a good team; 3. Chaos and uncertainty are bad for business and workers.

It’s just another week in Congress and another attack on women’s health. For more than 40 years, #TitleX has helped vulnerable families in rural and underserved communities access the family planning care they need. A woman’s access to birth control shouldn’t be dependent on her income or zip code, but House leaders are determined to eradicate places where contraception is available.

Anyone who falls victim to physical, sexual or emotional violence — particularly children — deserves the opportunity to seek justice, regardless of who abused them. Today, I introduced a bill with Rep. Jaime Herrera Beutler to close a legal loophole that denies justice for some survivors of child abuse.

Just because tech advances have made it easier for the government to collect data doesn’t mean our privacy rights can or should be violated. I helped introduce the Stop Mass Hacking Act to reverse the DoJ’s changes to Rule 41.
The reports of plans to unravel employer health coverage for 177 million Americans would be devastating to the middle class. We must #ProtectOurCare.
Today, we remember a terrible part of our past and recommit to fight against such blatant violations of our values. #DayOfRemembrance
Happy #PresidentsDay! If you’re visiting DC and want a White House tour, contact my office for information.

Today, I called for answers on the accessibility of naloxone injectors, a life-saving tool in reducing #opioid overdose deaths. It’s critical these drugs remain affordable for the millions of families who are suffering from addiction.
Happy Birthday to #GeorgeWashington, the Father of our country and the namesake of our great state of #WA!

I am deeply disturbed by the recent wave of threats against Stroum Jewish Community Center of Greater Seattle and other JCCs around the country. I joined my colleagues in a letter to the administration urging swift action to address these threats. Antisemitism is unacceptable, and I will continue to speak out against this hatred.

I support Congressman Jerry Nadler's H.Res. 111 because the American people deserve to know the full extent of Russia's grip on the Trump administration. With the lack of transparency from this President, Congress must exercise its oversight responsibilities to ensure there isn’t improper influence by foreign entities. These are serious claims that easily merit an investigation and this should be a bipartisan effort. If there is nothing to hide, then they have nothing to fear.
It was great to meet with Nutrition First today to talk about the importance of improving access to healthy food and protecting #WIC.

In order to create jobs and provide economic security, Americans need certainty and stability – something that has been severely lacking in the first few weeks of this presidency. Tonight’s #JointSession was long on rhetoric and short on specifics. I will gladly work with Republicans on policies that strengthen the middle class and move our country forward. But I will not support efforts to roll back progress we've  made.
Happy birthday, Peace Corps! Thank you for your great work to help make our world a safer place by bringing our global communities together.

Too often, we forget the Affordable Care Act is about more than numbers. It’s about real people. In the coming weeks, I’ll be highlighting personal stories from my constituents about why the #ACA must be preserved — like Paul, from Snohomish, whose son-in-law died from cancer before the ACA passed. He delayed seeking care because his family couldn’t afford health insurance, and by the time he got covered, the disease had progressed too far. As Paul wrote to me, “The certificate of death states he died from cancer, but I believe he died from a broken healthcare system.”   We need to protect the ACA for families like Paul’s. Getting sick should never mean going bankrupt. If you haven’t yet, let me know how the ACA has helped you. https://delbene.house.gov/aca

If Attorney General Jeff Sessions lied under oath about his contacts with Russia during the campaign, he can’t be trusted to conduct an impartial investigation. We need an unbiased investigation into Russian involvement in our election.

Republicans are hiding their plan to dismantle the Affordable Care Act behind closed doors. The American people deserve the opportunity to review this dangerous proposal before it comes before Congress — especially the 30 million Americans who stand to lose their healthcare. That’s why I joined my colleagues in calling for a hearing on any #ACA repeal bill before it moves forward. We need answers and details to #ProtectOurCare.
I helped introduce the Women’s Health Protection Act to ensure a woman’s access to healthcare doesn’t depend on her income or zip code.

Did you know? 465,400 individuals in #WA01 with employer-sponsored health insurance are at risk of losing important consumer protections — like the prohibition on annual and lifetime limits and coverage of preexisting health conditions — if the #ACA is repealed.

Did you forget to file a federal tax return in 2013? The IRS still has $30,330,000 waiting for the 27,600 Washingtonians who didn’t file. Feel free to contact my Bothell office if you need assistance.
ICYMI: Cascades College and Career Academy has opened enrollment for their Job Corps pilot program.
We already have strong vetting procedures in place. President Donald J. Trump’s new executive order is no better than his first one. It is discriminatory and does not strengthen our security.
The Affordable Care Act has helped lower the uninsured rate from 11.1% to 5.1% in #WA01, a drop of 6 percentage points. #ProtectOurCare

It’s no wonder this bill was kept under lock and key until the very last second. Making seniors, working families, children and people with disabilities foot the bill for this poorly conceived experiment is just wrong. The lack of transparency in this process should concern every American. My constituents deserve the right to #ReadTheBill.

Staci, from Snoqualmie, got coverage through the healthcare exchange. She recently wrote to me and said, “Just last week I was diagnosed with breast cancer. I am terrified — not as much by the cancer as by the thought that we might not be able to pay for health insurance.” The Republican bill spells disaster for people like Staci. And as her representative in Congress, I will not stand for it.
It was an honor to join colleagues this past weekend on the Edmund Pettus Bridge to commemorate Foot Soldiers who marched for progress. #goodtrouble

The Committee on Ways and Means is marking up the GOP's #PayMoreForLess bill today without a CBO score saying how much the bill will cost or how many people stand to lose coverage. This is not how this is supposed to work.
Today, I'm wearing red in solidarity, and getting ready to defend a woman’s access to healthcare. #internationalwomensday #daywithoutawoman
Here's how the #PayMoreForLess bill would affect families like Diane's in Sumas, WA:

This dangerous legislation shouldn’t take effect if it results in higher costs for our nation’s #seniors. Older Americans are already struggling to keep up with rising costs today, and the GOP bill would dramatically increase their insurance premiums and out-of-pocket costs while undermining the long-term solvency of #Medicare.

If my colleagues are truly concerned about states’ rights and state flexibility, they should support the amendment to protect states like Washington that have thrived under Democratic reforms that are helping millions of working families, seniors and children.

Families who live in rural communities already face a number of substantial barriers to healthcare, often having to travel long distances to reach the nearest hospital or urgent care center — sometimes even to reach their primary care physician. The last thing we should be doing is putting access to healthcare farther out of reach for middle-class families in rural America.

My amendment with Rep. Linda Sánchez would have, once and for all, repealed a tax that both Democrats and Republicans agree isn’t working — because we know it harms the middle class. The Cadillac Tax is a perfect example of how we could be working together to make targeted improvements to our healthcare laws, rather than the damaging changes we’re considering today. Healthcare is too important to simply pass an inferior law so you can tell people you checked a box, rather than offering real solutions.

“All we've been talking so far has been repealing a tax on tanning beds, repealing a tax on insurance companies, creating a cost of $1 billion to the Treasury and doing nothing to address the health care of my constituents, and that's very concerning to me.”

Tanning beds, Congressman Jason Smith? Really? Your biggest concern for women's health is paying too much for tanning? How about real healthcare? We should be focusing on health plans that provide coverage of vital women’s health services — including birth control at no cost. Not only does contraception help women plan their families, it’s also used for a variety of other health reasons, like treating endometriosis. Milynda from Kenmore told me, “Don’t deny a woman her right to affordable birth control. Because maybe, just maybe, it’s something that could help save her life.”

Defunding Planned Parenthood will do nothing but harm our nation’s most vulnerable — particularly those in rural and underserved communities. That’s why I introduced an amendment to ensure Americans continue to have access to life-saving care through Planned Parenthood. Politicians have no place interfering in a woman’s most personal medical decisions, including decisions about when and where to get her healthcare. It’s time for the never-ending attacks on women’s health to stop, once and for all.
I wasn’t in Congress when the #ACA was passed. I care about TODAY. This GOP bill will mean coverage for fewer people and you’ll #PayMoreForLess.

I am deeply distraught by the Majority’s attempt to cut more than $100 billion from #Medicare and reduce its solvency by three years. Medicare is a vital program that more than 50 million Americans depend on, including 90,000 in #WA01. Seniors deserve better. They deserve policymakers who are willing to work across the aisle on improvements to the program — like allowing Medicare to negotiate drug prices to bring down the cost of prescriptions.

Six weeks ago, millions of women took to the streets and marched in communities — hand-in-hand with their husbands, brothers and fathers — to send a clear signal to President Trump and members of Congress:   "Hear our voices. Respect our bodies. Protect our rights"  Unfortunately, the #PayMoreForLess bill is riddled with dangerous, ideological attacks that undermine women’s safety & their constitutional right to choose.

As a former businesswoman, I know firsthand that when #smallbusinesses and #startups get the tools and opportunity to succeed, America’s economy is stronger. My amendment stops the GOP bill from making it even more difficult for small business owners to provide #healthcare to their employees. Instead, it offers meaningful help to these entrepreneurs and their workers. I would hope all members of the Committee can support it. Instead of repealing Americans’ healthcare, we should be taking up commonsense fixes to make the law work better. That’s precisely what my amendment will do.

Since coming to Congress, I have worked tirelessly to find commonsense fixes to our nation’s healthcare laws. We should build upon the reforms we’ve already made to expand coverage and reduce costs. But what my colleagues on the other side of the aisle have put forward would make working families, seniors, children and people with disabilities foot the bill for their poorly conceived experiment. Instead of making smart reforms to ensure all Americans have access to affordable health coverage, Republicans are forcing people to #PayMoreForLess. This certainly isn’t “insurance for everybody,” as the President promised.

Innovations in healthcare — like precision medicine — are offering today’s patients some of the greatest medical breakthroughs seen in generations. I believe Congress must be responsive to the rapidly changing delivery of healthcare to ensure #Medicare and #Medicaid are covering and reimbursing care the way it works today. That’s why I wrote to the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services urging them to look into improving access to genetic testing and patient outcomes through precision medicine.

This past week, the Ways and Means Committee passed the GOP’s #PayMoreForLess bill, which will increase healthcare costs and cut coverage for millions of Americans. My colleagues and I spent 18 hours introducing amendments to help working families, seniors, children and people with disabilities who will be negatively impacted by this bill, but Republicans blocked all of these efforts in their rush to jam it through without a cost estimate from the Congressional Budget Office.   So, next Wednesday, I’ll be in the House Budget Committee markup, again trying to get answers and fighting to protect the tens of millions of Americans who are about to lose their coverage, and the millions more who will suffer from sky-rocketing costs.
It's great to be at #SxSW to talk about the complex opportunities & challenges facing us while crafting policy in #artificialintelligence.
As a Girl Scouts alumna, I know the importance of having opportunities to develop leadership skills. Happy birthday and thank you for all you do!

I joined Congressman Hakeem Jeffries and Rep. Ted Lieu on a Resolution Of Inquiry seeking any information regarding President Trump and his administration’s connections with Russia. Members of Congress have a responsibility to the country to get real answers from the Trump administration.
The U.S. Congressional Budget Office score confirms this is a dangerous and irresponsible bill that would rip healthcare away from 24,000,000 people.
Happy #PiDay! I'm joining Rep. Bill Foster in a resolution recognizing the importance of math and science education in our schools. #STEM
It was great to meet with Kirkland, WA - Government & City of Lake Stevens, WA today to discuss how we can work together to support the communities in #WA01!

I’m standing with House Budget Committee Democrats to protect American families whose lives and financial stability are being threatened by the GOP’s destructive proposal. We should build upon the reforms we’ve already made to expand coverage and reduce costs — not destabilize our nation’s healthcare system, rob 24 million of their health insurance and increase costs for seniors, women and the middle class. Instead of making smart reforms to ensure all Americans have access to affordable health coverage, the GOP is forcing people to #PayMoreForLess

The #PayMoreForLess bill would decimate #Medicaid, ripping healthcare away from 600,000 people in my home state of #WA, including 36,000 in #WA01. People like Katie, my constituent from Bothell, who had coverage for maternity care thanks to Medicaid expansion. While her daughter was born happy and healthy, Katie told me: “I honestly can’t imagine what I would have done without Medicaid.”   This bill takes coverage away from women, children, seniors, and people with disabilities – and gives them nothing in return. “Access” to unaffordable coverage is not healthcare. It’s a false promise.

Last Congress, I sat through the unbelievable 15-month charade of a Select Committee whose sole purpose was to spread false information about Planned Parenthood. Today, the Majority is continuing their reckless campaign by denying lifesaving care to Americans, simply because they oppose a woman’s constitutionally protected right to choose. Sometimes it seems like all this chamber does is attack women’s health, but let me be clear – politicians do not have the right to make healthcare decisions for women. It’s that simple.

One of the most unconscionable parts of this incredibly dangerous bill is that it directly attacks seniors and the #Medicare program. Medicare is a lifeline for more than 58 million Americans, including 90,000 people in my district alone, like Doris and Lance from Kirkland, and Grace from Redmond. I introduced a motion that would protect seniors and Medicare by eliminating the irresponsible provision that robs the Medicare trust fund of $170 billion. If this bill goes forward, with this provision intact, robbing the Medicare trust fund and damaging the program’s future – it’s Doris, Lance, Grace and so many others like them who will be harmed.

The President’s #budget is light on detail, but it clearly outlines enormous setbacks in nearly every area affecting our economy. This budget proposal would have a negative impact on critical research, our environment, affordable housing programs and the arts, to name just a few. We need to strengthen our country through strategic investments in education, research, clean energy and infrastructure, not reckless and draconian cuts.

Great to join Congresswoman Pramila Jayapal in hosting a group of heroic DC Bully Busters from the Seattle-area and signing their pledge to help #stopbullying! I’m a firm believer that words matter. And we need elected officials who understand that & respect the important contributions others make. The DC Bully Busters are doing an amazing job and I would hope all lawmakers agree to sign their #antibullying pledge.

Late last night, Republicans inserted a dangerous provision in their #PayMoreForLess bill that allows states to tell new mothers to find work within 60 days of childbirth — or lose coverage. No mother should be forced to spend the first days after childbirth applying for jobs, rather than caring for her newborn. Today, I joined Joe Biden & House Democrats to mark the passage and signing of the #AffordableCareAct seven years ago. I'm committed to working with my colleagues to build on the reforms we’ve already made to expand coverage and reduce healthcare costs. Instead, the GOP's #PayMoreForLess bill raises out-of-pocket costs, guts seniors' benefits and leaves 24 million more Americans uninsured. Here's how it affects #WA:

In their rush to check a political box, Republicans are making drastic cuts to Americans’ healthcare behind closed doors to appease the most extreme members of Congress. And in the last 24 hours, their #PayMoreForLess bill has gone from bad to worse. Gutting insurance coverage for essential healthcare like prescription drugs, ER services and annual check-ups — while hiking premiums & deductibles — does nothing but hurt middle-class families. My constituents deserve better.

If the House Republicans had crafted a bill that lived up to President Donald J. Trump’s promise of insurance for everyone — at lower cost — they'd have bipartisan support today. But that’s not what they did. Their bill, slapped together haphazardly to check a political box, forces Americans to #PayMoreForLess. I’m not voting against this because it’s a GOP bill. I’m voting 'NO' because — by any objective metric — it will harm families and our healthcare system.

I’m relieved we were able to stop this dangerous legislation before it completely destabilized our nation’s healthcare system. Since coming to Congress, I have worked tirelessly to find commonsense fixes to our nation’s healthcare laws. We should build upon the reforms we’ve already made to expand coverage and reduce costs — this bill did none of that. Instead, most Americans would end up paying more for less, while millions more will find coverage completely out of reach.

I’m pleased the House passed the bipartisan PNW Earthquake Preparedness Act today to ensure FEMA Federal Emergency Management Agency develops a plan for an earthquake early warning system to help reduce the devastating toll of earthquakes and tsunamis.

Protecting American's right to #privacy has been a top priority for me since coming to Congress. That's why I oppose S.J. Res 34 because people have the right to #BroadbandPrivacy. Today I'm voting in support of a resolution that would force the release of President Trump’s tax returns. This President is breaking 40 years of precedent with his alarming lack of financial transparency, and his refusal to release his tax returns is a serious red flag. Given the President’s evasive maneuvering, Congress has a constitutional responsibility to obtain the records needed to perform rigorous, unbiased oversight. If the President is serious about working on tax reform, people deserve to know what conflicts of interest – foreign or domestic – may influence his decision-making. If he has nothing to hide, why not release his returns?

I’ll continue to #StandWithPP against any attempts to strip federal funding for the services they provide to our communities. #PinkOut
I’m voting 'NO' on #HR1430 and #HR1431. Let's #DefendScience, not deny it. The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency needs independent research, not ‘alternative facts,’ to do its job.

The opioid epidemic is having a devastating impact on public health and safety across the United States. That’s why I signed a bipartisan letter urging appropriators to fund the Comprehensive Addiction and Recovery Act, including my amendment to expand community-based substance use diversion programs — based on King County’s successful LEAD model. It’s time to provide the resources necessary for states and local governments to expand treatment, prevention and recovery efforts for the millions of Americans who are affected by addiction.

Today, I met with Dennis, a constituent and Coast Guard veteran. He shared with me the struggles and frustrations he has faced navigating the system. My office has spent years helping him with his VA benefits appeal. Congress can and must do moreto streamline the VA’s burdensome appeals process for veterans like Dennis.

It is incredibly disappointing that President Trump is looking into easing restrictions on offshore drilling, including in areas currently protected by the Antiquities Act. That’s why I’ve joined Congressman Jared Huffman and other colleagues in introducing the West Coast Ocean Protection Act. This bill would explicitly prohibit any offshore drilling activities along the Outer Continental Shelf of the West Coast.

#LGBT Americans don’t need a ‘cure,’ they need #equality. That’s why I joined Rep. Ted Lieu in reintroducing the Therapeutic Fraud Prevention Act to ban so-called “conversion therapy.” There is no scientific basis or evidence for this fraudulent and harmful practice.

It’s bad enough that House Republicans’ latest plan to dismantle the Affordable Care Act will eliminate protections for pre-existing conditions. But it’s appalling that their plan allows members of Congress to keep those protections while denying the American people the same. #ProtectOurCare
We need bipartisan, fiscally responsible #taxreform, not a tax code that benefits only the wealthiest Americans at the expense of working families.

I agree with the Everett Herald. Our beautiful public lands are part of what makes living in the Pacific Northwest so special. President Trump should “leave national monuments as they are.” #MonumentsForAll
I joined Progressive Policy Institute and Technology Policy Institute to discuss how we should encourage policies that ensure information flows freely across borders. #digitaltrade

Hard to believe, but House GOP leaders found a way to make their reckless healthcare proposal even more destructive this week. Stripping protections for pre-existing conditions and essential health benefits is more than just a broken promise — it spells disaster for millions of Americans who rely on the Affordable Care Act to stay alive, including hundreds of thousands in Washington state. It’s time for Republicans to abandon their quest to repeal the #ACA and start working across the aisle to improve our healthcare system and ensure all Americans have affordable, quality health coverage.
Rep. Chris Collins & I led a bipartisan letter urging President Trump to support dairy farmers in #WA01 and across the country.

For too long, local brick and mortar businesses have been at an unfair competitive disadvantage to out-of-state online retailers. I introduced the #RTPA to help local communities recover lost revenue that can fund our schools and infrastructure.
In order to protect our environment, we must address the challenge that #climatechange poses without delay. It's time to #ActOnClimate.
President Trump's first 100 days have been chaotic and confusing for families and businesses. But one thing is clear — he’s consistently ignored the middle class.
Sad news from #WA today – my heart goes out to the family of former Governor Mike Lowry.
I introduced a bill to create a Joint Commission on #NorthKorea as a diplomatic effort to stop their hostile actions.

In too many states, #LGBT Americans can still be fired, denied credit and evicted from their home simply because of who they are and who they love. Today, I helped reintroduce the #EqualityAct. We can’t stop fighting until all Americans have equal rights and protections. #EqualityForward

Jimmy Kimmel is right: “No parent should ever have to decide if they can afford to save their child’s life.” I’ve heard the same from hundreds of my constituents — like Christine, from Kirkland, who was also born with a congenital heart defect. Christine told me that before the #ACA, she used to cry herself to sleep thinking about the bankruptcy she would face just to stay alive. We cannot repeal the #ACA for families like Christine’s, and Jimmy’s, and so many others. #ProtectOurCare
I'm pleased to launch the #RealityCaucus to explore the potential to reshape how we use #VirtualReality and #AugmentedReality to interact in the world.

Today, the House passed the FY17 #omnibus, which includes some of the critical investments I have fought for, such as increased funding for National Institutes of Health (NIH) and the #opioidcrisis. But unfortunately, this bill only funds the government through September, meaning Congress has less than 5 months to act before another potential spending fight. As a member of the House Budget Committee, I hope we can end this inefficient cycle of governing from crisis to crisis, and finally provide the certainty that our families & businesses need to succeed.

Stripping protections for the 133 million Americans with pre-existing conditions isn’t just wrong. It’s inhumane. This isn’t about politics — it’s about human decency and who we are as Americans. Nobody should go bankrupt just to afford the medical care they need to stay alive. I hope my colleagues on both sides of the aisle find the courage and wisdom to vote against this dangerous legislation today. If you haven’t already, contact your members of Congress and make your voice heard. #ProtectOurCare

It’s outrageous that despite promises of “insurance for everybody,” House Republicans passed a reckless healthcare bill that causes 24 million Americans to lose care. The #AHCA isn’t just bad policy — it’s inhumane. Nobody should face bankruptcy just to afford the medical care they need to stay alive. I hope the Senate has the courage and wisdom to stop this destructive bill before it hurts Americans and destabilizes our #healthcare system.

It’s deeply troubling that President Trump has issued yet another ideological attack on a woman’s right to make her own #healthcare decisions. A woman’s boss should never be the one to make medical decisions for her – these decisions should be between her and her doctor.
Each May, we celebrate National #FosterCareMonth – a month to recommit to ensuring every child has a safe, loving home. #FosterYouthVoices

Happy #SmallBusinessWeek! Whether it's helping small business owners with the cost of health insurance for their workers, or ensuring women entrepreneurs have equal access to the tools and resources they need, I’m working on policies that help grow our local economy by supporting #smallbiz & #entrepreneurs.
I’m pleased to announce that four U.S. military academies have accepted the nominations of nine #WA01 high school students & graduates!
Thank you, #WA01, for staying engaged and making your voices heard! As always, please feel free to share your thoughts via mail, email or phone.

As I told seattlepi.com, it’s appalling that men in the Senate are once again making decisions about women’s healthcare without their input or consultation. For everyone's sake, I hope they come to their senses and allow women at the table. What the House passed last week represents one of the most regressive policies for women in generations. It guts coverage for essential benefits like pregnancy and maternity care, imposes sweeping restrictions on reproductive care, defunds Planned Parenthood and allows discrimination against breast cancer survivors and women with pre-existing conditions. Millions of women marched in January to demand their voices be heard, and they will not remain silent while their healthcare is decimated by Congress. #ProtectOurCare

As someone who used to work in tech – and as a self-proclaimed geek – women in STEM is a topic near to my heart. Today, I joined #CCBWG members to talk about ensuring all kids, especially young women of color, have opportunities to succeed in #STEM. For our country to remain a leader in innovation we’ll need a diverse, creative workforce full of people with different backgrounds.

I talked with members of AmeriCorps today about the crucial work they do in #WA01 communities and across the country. It’s shameful that the President is proposing the elimination of critical service programs like AmeriCorps. Instead of gutting these job-creating investments in affordable housing, environmental recovery and disaster relief — which give us a great return on our investment — we should be strengthening  Corporation for National and Community Service programs like #AmeriCorps and #Senior Corps.
I was honored to join colleagues & tribal members in celebrating the return of the remains of the Ancient One to the Columbia Basin tribes.
A big 'THANK YOU' to the National Association of Letter Carriers for your successful #StampOutHunger food drive in #Bothell!
From my family to yours, happy #MothersDay!
I'm saddened to hear of the passing of Carol Newhouse, wife of Congressman Dan Newhouse. My thoughts and prayers are with him and his family and friends.

I’m dismayed that, during #WomensHealthWeek no less, the White House has announced a dangerous expansion of the Global Gag Rule — denying funding to non-government organizations that provide needed medical care to women and families. This action will directly harm vulnerable women around the world, and undermine our efforts to promote U.S. interests abroad through global health assistance. #TrumpGlobalGag

If the news reports of the President revealing highly classified information to Russians are true, he risked the public's safety. The American people deserve to know if these troubling reports are true. Republicans and Democrats in Congress need to approve an independent investigation.

Today, I signed a discharge petition to force a vote on the bipartisan #ProtectingOurDemocracy Act to create an independent commission to investigate Trump and Russia. Facts shouldn’t be partisan. We need an unbiased investigation to get answers for the American people. I urge all my colleagues to sign on.

I helped introduce the #BankonStudents Act to allow families to refinance their student debt. It’s unacceptable that Americans can refinance car loans and mortgages but can't take advantage of lower interest rates on #studentloans. If we want students to succeed, we need to work toward commonsense solutions that make a college degree more affordable for all.
A special prosecutor is an important step in getting to the truth, and an independent commission is still needed to prevent Russian meddling in future elections. #ProtectOurDemocracy
I’ve pushed to update our laws to work in today’s world. I'm pleased the House passed the bipartisan #MGTechnology Act to modernize gov IT.
I’m disappointed by today’s Federal Communications Commission vote to start efforts to repeal #netneutrality. I oppose these efforts and will work to protect a free and open internet. #SavetheNet

The complexity of our current tax code is paid for on the backs of working families and small businesses. There’s no question that our tax laws are in desperate need of thoughtful reform, which is why I’m glad the House Ways and Means Committee finally held a hearing today. Comprehensive tax reform should not mean tilting the scale even more toward the wealthiest. It should put middle-class families first, with fairness for all Americans regardless of their income or zip code. And if we want to provide long-term financial stability that gives working families and businesses the ability to plan for the future in this changing economy, this must be a bipartisan effort.

Whether it’s red raspberries, spinach, potatoes or any number of different fruits and vegetables grown by our local farmers, specialty crops play a critical part in western Washington’s economy. That’s why I introduced a resolution to acknowledge the significant effect specialty crops play in both the local and national economy. And I will continue to be a tireless advocate for specialty crop programs that ensure we have a vibrant agricultural industry.
It was a honor to help kick off the Arthritis Foundation's Puget Sound Walk to Cure #Arthritis. By investing in research we can make a difference.
Through the Stilly 2000 Youth Project, Arlington, Washington has a new BGCA Club to improve academic achievement and strengthen our community.
Today, I discussed the need for affordable housing to reduce #homelessness in Snohomish County with YWCA Seattle King Snohomish. We cannot gut these vital programs.
Join me and my colleagues in celebrating the 400,000 youth in foster care and those who make a difference in their lives. #FosterYouthVoices
My thoughts are with Manchester today. Together, we will stand up to hate wherever it appears. #WeStandTogether

The President’s budget jeopardizes the middle class by gutting funding for basic necessities like healthcare, nutrition, housing and education. This budget is an enormous setback in nearly every area affecting American families, particularly children, seniors and people with disabilities. It would have a negative impact on critical research, healthcare, job training, our environment, affordable housing programs and education, just to name a few. Rather than gouging programs the middle class relies on to give the wealthiest a tax cut, we should be working on a bipartisan budget that provides working families certainty and stability through strategic investments. This budget is as irresponsible as it is dangerous.
Today, I questioned Director Mulvaney about the draconian #TrumpCuts to programs critical for my constituents and people around the country.

Today’s Congressional Budget Office report is a stark reminder of just how reckless House Republicans were to pass the #AHCA without knowing its impact on American families. This confirms the #AHCA is a dangerous and irresponsible bill that torpedoes protections for pre-existing conditions, robs millions of their health insurance and raises costs for working families, seniors, women and people with disabilities. I hope the Senate has the courage and wisdom to stop this ill-conceived legislation before it destabilizes our healthcare system.

We need to support innovative policies that address the rapidly changing workforce to ensure we have an economy that works for everyone. I joined Senator Mark Warner in introducing a bill to test-drive ways we can improve the portability of benefits for today’s gig economy workforce. Whether someone makes a living through mobile car services or by selling crafts online, they deserve access to benefits typically provided by traditional full-time employment.

I often hear from constituents struggling with the rising cost of child care – some even deciding to leave the workforce because the costs exceed their wages. That’s why I’ve joined Congressman Danny K. Davis in introducing legislation to expand the Child and Dependent Care Tax Credit, which helps grow our middle class.

Eliminating nutrition assistance for people trying to find work doesn’t help if jobs are not available. That’s why I introduced the SNAP Work Opportunity Act to protect – not punish – these individuals. By helping people find good-paying, long-term employment in a high-demand industry we can ensure everyone has access to basics like food and shelter.

I talked with two mothers and a pediatrician today about the harmful impacts the #AHCA will have on kids and people with preexisting conditions. We should work on improving our current healthcare system, not stripping away coverage and protections from millions of our most vulnerable.
It was great to join Cascade Bicyle and thousands of others on the 2017 #EmeraldBikeRide to support a healthy, local community!
I held a roundtable with #WA01 farmers today to discuss how we can work together to support the 160K jobs tied to agriculture in #WA.
Today, I had the opportunity to tour Unity Care NW and talk with their staff about the need to support the work of community health centers.

Thanks to PROTECT, National Center for Victims of Crime, National Children's Alliance, National Coalition Against Domestic Violence, and RAINN for your letter in support of my & Jaime Herrera Beutler's bill, #HR1103. Our bipartisan bill helps child abuse survivors seek justice. I hope House Armed Services Committee Republicans and House Armed Services Committee Democrats work together to pass it without delay.
It was great to tour local company American Preparedness today to talk about how our country can better support #veteran-owned businesses.
I'm fighting to protect #netneutrality and a free and open internet. Federal Communications Commission Chairman Pai should not move us backward.
#Birthcontrol is a critical component of women’s healthcare. And a woman’s boss should never be the one to make healthcare decisions for her.
Today, I spoke with the Northshore School District #PTA about the critical role that families play in their kids’ education. As a former PTA mom, thank you!
While the President ignores the reality of #climatechange, it's up to states to step up for our planet's future.

The President’s irresponsible and dangerous budget eliminates vital funding for preparedness efforts like earthquake warning systems. That’s why Congressman Adam Schiff,  Peter DeFazio and I sent a letter urging him to restore investments that help protect our communities in times of disaster. Earthquake early warning systems are smart investments that not only save lives, but also prevent higher costs from damage caused by major earthquakes.
Thanks for the flight today, Air Method and Airlift NW! Look forward to working with you to support access to life-saving air ambulance services — particularly in rural communities throughout #WA01.

I spoke at Jackson School of International Studies at University of Washington and Trade Development Alliance of Greater Seattle conference today about updating our #tech policies and infrastructure and how #CyberSecurity needs to be a global effort.
Today, I #wearorange. It’s far past time for Congress to take action to protect our communities from the tragic cycle of gun violence.
I toured VRstudios to discuss how their industry  and the Congressional #RealityCaucus can work together to support innovation in #virtualreality and #augmentedreality.
Happy #Pride2017! Each June, we celebrate the #LGBT community and the progress we’ve made while recognizing there is much more to be done.

The repeal of #DADT and anti-LGBT policies in our military means our #veteran population is becoming more diverse. “There are things about Affordable Care Act that are vital to kids like Colton who has been battling high-risk Leukemia for the past eight years and is currently in his fifth remission. He has fought so hard not only to survive, but thrive through the challenges life has already thrown at him in his 17 years of life. He will always have a ‘pre-existing condition’ that demands high quality healthcare and to think that could go away for him and many like him is criminal. The ACA isn’t perfect, but the groundwork that was laid is working for many and we simply need to sit down and figure out how to make changes to it so it works for more Americans. The answer is NOT to take away coverage for pre-existing conditions, it is NOT to reapply lifetime maximums to health plans and it is NOT to take money away from Medicaid. Having HOPE in the future has gotten Colton through many very tough days that looked gloomy and we owe it to him to have a health plan that gives him…HOPE in his future knowing that he will always get the healthcare he needs to continue to thrive and survive.”   That’s what Colton’s mother, Suzy, wrote to me today. I will keep working to #ProtectOurCare and I hope enough senators come to their senses before voting to harm middle-class families like Colton’s.

Healthcare is not a privilege reserved for those fortunate enough to be born wealthy or healthy. It is a human right. And it is worth fighting for. To families across the country who are terrified by what the Senate healthcare repeal bill means for them, I can promise you — we’re not backing down. #ProtectOurCare

When I heard Pennie's story, I was shocked there was a legal loophole denying justice for survivors of child abuse. That’s why I introduced a bill with Rep. Jaime Herrera Beutler to ensure justice for all survivors of these horrific acts, regardless of who abused them. Today we took an important step in moving this bipartisan solution forward by adding it to the #NDAA with help from Congressman Rick Larsen. Because it’s simply unacceptable that current law shields some convicted child abusers from paying the restitution they owe.

At just the age of two, Sammy has already received more than $500,000 in medical care for his Severe Hemophilia A. Sammy’s mother wrote to me saying, “We want our son to be able to run, play, explore, learn, grow, and become an incredible person. Without access to his doctors and expensive daily medication regimen, Sammy would not be able to run around without experiencing excruciatingly painful joint bleeds and/or life threatening spontaneous hemorrhaging. The House and now Senate's proposed healthcare reform threaten my son's life by removing critical protections that the ACA affords him.”   Allowing providers to once again put lifetime caps on care would be taking our country backward, not forward, and would force families like Sammy’s to face bankruptcy or forego the care their loved ones need to survive. Children like him are the reason I’m fighting to #ProtectOurCare from the Republicans’ healthcare repeal bill. It isn’t just mean, it’s immoral.

It is incredibly disappointing that Republicans are pushing partisan legislation and denying Democrats a seat at the table on a major policy debate that touches every American’s life. There is no question that our tax laws are in desperate need of thoughtful reform. Done properly, #taxreform could eliminate inequities in the code, and give working families and small businesses some certainty so they can plan their futures. But comprehensive tax reform does not mean tilting the scale even more toward the wealthiest as this plan would. Comprehensive tax reform should be permanent, and put middle-class families first.   If Republicans truly want to accomplish something that has a real, lasting impact on families and businesses across the country, they will abandon this partisan approach and instead reach across the aisle to allow a collaborative, open process.

As students return to campus, I reintroduced the #EBOOK Act to lower college costs by encouraging the use of digital course materials. Textbooks are an often overlooked driver of the rising cost of college. In addition to addressing tuition hikes and burdensome student debt, we need to keep looking for solutions to the other factors making a college degree less attainable for working families.

I believe we need real tax reform that supports economic growth, starting with a stronger middle class. But the Ryan-McConnell plan fails that test, and now we know why. Ryan, McConnell and the White House clearly don’t understand the current realities of American families, whose median incomes are $55,000, not $100,000. The families I hear from are thinking about how to make ends meet, not a new granite counter top. Americans across the country are budgeting down to the penny each month to get food on the table, put their kids through school and save for retirement, and they are the ones who tax reform should be about. We need real tax reform for real people, not broken promises to those who need relief the most.

The #GOPtaxbill eliminates the adoption tax credit, which helped bring together Tiffani and Emmanuel with their son Dave from Liberia. Tiffani told me “There were many unexpected costs that came up and we had to take time off of work which resulted in loss of income." She continued, "There are many other families in the same situation. If there wasn't a tax credit available I know it would prevent other families that I've connected with to be able to adopt again in the future."

Tracie, a teacher at a #WA01 middle school in Whatcom County, told me how important the educator expense deduction is to her and her students. Tracie said, "This year I was moved to a room that was basically bare bones. I was reimbursed $100 from the district, but had also planned on the tax deduction to alleviate the pain. I don't have a lot of money, but my students deserve to be in a welcoming environment so we do what we have to do as teachers to provide a learning space that is inviting."
I offered an amendment to the #GOPtaxbill to repeal the Cadillac Tax on healthcare plans, which harms working families, such as first responders.

Supreme Court Justice Oliver Wendell Holmes Jr. once said, “Taxes are what we pay for civilized society.” The purpose of the tax code is not to give special breaks to corporations and the wealthiest, but to fund a functioning government & support an environment where every #middleclass family can succeed.  But the #GOPtaxbill undercuts the very notion of a civilized society. It is morally bankrupt, and an outright attack on the middle class, built on a foundation of lies and mischaracterizations. I will not accept this, and based on what I’m hearing from my constituents, neither will the American people.

Short version of this week's #GOPtaxbill markup:     ➡️D introduces amendment.    ➡️Rs say it's a good amendment, but now isn't the right time - vote NAY.    ➡️Rinse, repeat.  So tell me, when is the right time if not in a Ways & Means markup?   This is not #taxreform. This is a #GOPTaxScam.

Today, I introduced a bill to eliminate tax breaks that allow corporations to deduct payments related to sexual misconduct, taking one step toward incentivizing real solutions rather than a system of sweeping harassment under the rug. For too long settlements have been paid by powerful figures to victims of sexual misconduct in exchange for their signing non-disclosure agreements, keeping perpetrators’ reputations intact and company names out of headlines. As a society, if we’re going to demand corporations do their part in creating a culture that encourages people to come forward and report abuses, we need transparency and accountability, not subsidized settlements and silence.

The #GOPTaxScam raises taxes on millions of middle class Americans and explodes the debt, leaving our kids to foot the bill, all for a corporate tax cut. As this reckless bill goes to conference, I'll keep fighting for bipartisan #taxreform that puts families first, not special interests.

We've known funding will expire this Friday since we passed a Continuing Resolution two months ago. And yet, House Republicans plan to bring up another short-term CR – this time for just two weeks – kicking the can down the road yet again. As a former businesswoman, I know firsthand, no one would run their business for just two weeks at a time and neither should the government. It's long past time for Congress to put an end to this inefficient cycle and start encouraging economic growth and opportunity.

I don’t care if you’re a celebrity, a Member of Congress, a Supreme Court Justice or the President of the United States – there should be zero tolerance for sexual misconduct. The #silencebreakers who have summoned enormous courage to expose the abusers and say #MeToo rightfully deserve our recognition for the role they're playing in what will hopefully become a sea change in our society. Let's not let this opportunity slip away.
